column1: 333039;instagram;2018-09-28 16:21:01;FALSE;"do your kids help out? do your boys help? lots of lively
column2: heartfelt and passionate discussion yesterday around dr. ford and her testimony. as a mom of two boys
column3: i am dedicated to raising them not only to respect women for their true value and to lead by example but also to teach them to be helpful
column5: engaged participants in family life. that way
column6: i am equipping them to acknowledge and assist people outside our family and in their broader community.

column1: i don’t pick up after my 6 year old son
column2: and though it takes a lot of encouragement
column3: he is responsible for putting away his toys and putting his clothes in the hamper. he also has started to clear the table at night. he enjoys it and feels proud of his contribution. he’s also taught to do things for himself
column4: which has given him a sense of pride. he dresses himself
column6: and showers independently. i know these are small things
column7: but i believe that these small things mean a whole lot. step two after speaking up for our value is showing men how to treat us. it sometimes seems too late for the grown ups
column8: but if i can teach independence
column11: it feels like i’m making some progress. .

column1: 333040;instagram;2018-09-28 16:21:02;FALSE;once when i had this painting on display at a show a man approached me and wanted to know what the inspiration was. my throat and stomach tightened up immediately. i managed to tell him it’s hard for me to articulate the story behind this one eloquently and he could find that information available on my website. he was unimpressed and immediately walked away. that conversation has stuck out to me to this day. i couldn’t manage to tell him the story behind dreamed before because it’s inspiration is so connected with my experience of being sexually assaulted. this piece allowed me to process and honor the emotions associated with this horrific event
column2: and explore the various facets of human nature. this painting helped me turn darkness into light. i couldn’t tell that man in a one-on-one conversation. i had a hard time telling my parents what happened the day after. i still have difficulty speaking of it
column4: surrounded by people who love me... i can’t imagine what christine ford went through telling her story with the entire world watching. #believesurvivors #girlgaze #metoo #christineblaseyford;;en;#believesurvivors

333043;instagram;2018-09-28 16:21:10;FALSE;honored & proud to support @iamwomankind through my work.
ever since #metoo i’ve been silent. as thrilled as i am about the awareness
column2: it’s triggering af. just because i found my power and voice it doesn’t mean i’ll ever forget. i can’t forget how the first time my then friends gaslighted me because he was a close friend
column3: and how the second time i said “no” on a first date and it didn’t matter.

column1: the last thing you want to do is tell someone because saying it out loud makes it real. and somehow you think it was your fault and you feel powerless and ashamed and stupid. you ask yourself how could you have let that happen? you’re just another statistic.

i’m lucky i have a best friend who is the definition of unconditional love and i’m lucky my insurance covers therapy. but i’ll never forget how isolated and lonely i felt during that period when i didn’t have the language

the news breaks my heart and if anything i hope the volume of stories shared helps people feel less alone and more empowered to seek resources and support. #believesurvivors #timesup #ibelievechristineblaseyford #womenwhodraw";;en;#metoo

column1: 333048;instagram;2018-09-28 16:24:23;FALSE;what has been most disturbing during the whole kavanaugh-ford hearing
column2: is the amount of people that seem to think that even if these allegations are true
column3: it shouldn’t cost kavanaugh the nomination
column4: that this type of behavior is apparently something that’s just synonymous with being a man. bull. shit. i am the youngest in my immediate and extended family with pretty much only older brothers and male cousins on both sides. this behavior never would be tolerated and the ‘locker room’ talk never uttered. it is not normal
column5: it is not acceptable and it is not something the women of this world should have to endure because it is so common place. the truth indeed matters and here’s hoping the senate does the right thing. ‘why did she wait so long?’ why does it matter? #metoo #timesup #justice #bigdeal;;en;#metoo

column1: you have the opportunity to choose. to decide how you want to perceive the world. accept how you feel but do not let your past define your future. every day is a new day

column3: you earned it when you were born. 🕊

column1: 333064;instagram;2018-09-28 16:26:09;FALSE;"be mindful that many women and girls you interact with may not have disclosed to you their survivor status. many of the women and girls you know may be feeling vulnerable

column1: 333096;instagram;2018-09-28 16:34:14;FALSE;"i never knew i could be so proud of a complete stranger. thank you dr. ford for your courage. i know you were only telling your truth
column2: but you spoke for the millions of women who have never had the opportunity to speak theirs. i watched every moment of yesterday’s hearing and much of it made me physically ill. i’ve grown up watching old
column4: privileged men run our country. as a white woman
column5: i’m sure i’ve benefited from some of that privilege. i’ve also been a victim of the misogyny perpetuated by that all male culture and a survivor of multiple sexual assaults and inappropriate sexual behavior. watching the hearings
column6: i was struck that every senator on the republican side was a wealthy white man over 50. many well over 70. many of the senators
column7: on both sides of the table
column8: have been serving since i was a toddler. i am 41 years old. we need term limits on the senate and we need to have diverse representation that reflects the population of our country. i kept thinking of a line from the suffragette song from mary poppins

column1: 333104;instagram;2018-09-28 16:35:01;FALSE;"i'm getting a little political today. there are no words for how this case makes me feel. this case makes me feel hopeless
column2: because it will always be easy to assume a woman is trying to use her tears and emotions to destroy a man. but i am here to tell you
column3: ladies... do not let them break you. white
column4: elite men have been traumatizing women since before the foundation of america
column5: and they have convinced us that women are sensitive and manipulative. and we have bought into that lie. and we have perpetuated that lie. how many women need to brave the media
column7: brave the hatred of the male sex before we finally believe them? there is a african proverb that sums up the issue of privilege here in america. ""until the lion learns how to write

column3: so i sent my bf to get him to help me. he came in our room
column4: rubbed and put some icy hot on my back. that was the start. the next day

column2: attempted rape** i've never told this story in detail. because it's taken this long to name its reality. but it's time.  #metoo . . . . .

column1: one night when i was in high school
column2: when my boyfriend and i were fooling around and making out

column1: he asked to pull down my pants and touch the tip of his penis to the opening of my vagina.
i was crying. i told him i didn’t want him to do it.  and he did anyway.
he said he wouldn’t stick it in; he just wanted to know what it felt like.
it has taken me 21 years to realize
column3: and name what he did as attempted rape.

column1: my guilt and shame for a sexual crime committed against me was a full-grown adult by the time i was far enough removed from purity culture and its demons to recognize and name it as sexual assault.
this week...i went back over the multiple times that boyfriend took my body from me
column2: and the multiple conversations i shared with his other ex-girlfriends in the wake of our breakup
column3: all of whom recounted similar incidents while dating him.

column1: and i wondered what i — what we — would do if he were the one interviewing for that position:
would we ultimately decide to let sleeping dogs lie for another 10 or 15 or 21 years?
or would one of us be brave enough to stand for all of us and send a letter to a senator
column3: and ask them to look into whether or not he took his pattern of behavior from high school with him into adulthood

column1: 333121;instagram;2018-09-28 16:40:00;FALSE;"this kavanaugh nightmare re-sends the message to all women that it's futile to try to get any justice or protection from a political & judiciary system that is hostile towards women. ef that! .
- demanding that we are seen as full humans with equal value to men.

- supporting other women! strong women empower other women. we must believe & hold each other up! - not prescribing to stereotypical beauty standards. - consuming products selectively & minimally (vote with your money in a world run by corporations).
- being clear with (educating) every guy i come across about how i expect & deserve to be treated. - calling out catcallers/rapists/creepy bosses/misogynists (easier said than done).
- questioning everything! from language (ms. -> mrs.) to chivalry to gender stereotypes.
- discussing these issues openly and often.
- holding guys accountable for their behavior. .

column1: 333122;instagram;2018-09-28 16:40:00;FALSE;i’ve been trying to figure out why the collective question of “why didn’t you report?” has been so triggering for me. it feels like a question that would only be asked by someone who isn’t listening and doesn’t ever intend to. ➰ the answering of the question is so woven up into the healing of the trauma itself
column2: and my resistance right now looks like allowing myself all of the time and space that i need to sort through that
column3: while staying present inside my body. ➰ it‘s not a real question. it’s another limb of their belief that it will always be our fault. ➰ i’ve been present when people have said #metoo for the first time ever
column4: and i know there are countless more who have yet to tell their stories. ➰ grief & sexuality are intimately entangled within most of our bodies. this is a reality i wish was not true but cannot be ignored. ➰ your trauma is not only legitimate if you can convince them of it or if they believe us. it already is. and you deserve all of the time and space you need to be with that. column1: 333166;instagram;2018-09-28 16:47:06;FALSE;"i wanted to take some time to talk about the kavanaugh hearing that i’m sure has been on everyone’s mind.
how messed up is it that we live in a world where survivors have to share the details of their trauma to be believed? and even then so are questioned in a manner to try and discredit them?
someone who even has an allegation against them should not be allowed to hold a position of power
column2: and there should always be serious investigations that follow but it’s this bullshit that prevents so many survivors from coming forward.

column1: why would you put yourself through rehashing the trauma you have worked so hard to overcome
column2: make an action that will undoubtedly change your life
column3: to come forward and speak your truth if it’s not true? that doesn’t make sense. especially when you know your actions will rarely cause a difference. less than 50% of college survivors who press charges against their assaulters

column1: those questioning dr ford’s experience and those who question other survivors and their stories sicken me.

column2: i want to remind you to take time for yourself. i was lucky to finish all my experiments before 3pm yesterday so i got to eat comfort food and lay in bed and watch netflix. take time for yourself; self care is super important and it’s more than okay to take a break.

column1: there is so much work that needs to be done. the world is still such a messed up place. but do your part
column2: and vote. don’t be complacent. be part of the change. ..

column1: 333174;instagram;2018-09-28 16:50:58;FALSE;"“i am here today not because i want to be. i am terrified.”

i believe christine blasey ford and as a fellow survivor i can testify as to how hard it is to publicly acknowledge a secret that has haunted you for your entire life. i know this is not the way she would have preferred to share her truth and i am humbled by her bravery. the pressure she faced was intense and extreme much like the political careerists who rushed to polarize her account to play to their own personal agendas and advantage. brett kavanaugh was the biggest of these and stood the most to lose professionally but the complete lack of compassion in his own defence made his testimony difficult to watch. i would not want to encounter him on the bench if my son ever found himself in similar circumstances as dr. blasey-ford.
i’ve had a full day now to let this all sink in and i have to say that the whole affair has left me feeling very sad.

we now live in a world of “fake news” and “alternate facts” where the truth has become a moving target eagerly manipulated by those seeking to personally gain something from it. i have learned from personal experience that the truth is what matters most and it is impossible to move forward without really facing it. christine blasey-ford was sexually assaulted when she was 15 years old. yesterday
column3: she shared her truth publicly for the first time but instead of focusing on the her trauma
column4: the elected leaders of the american people saw it as an opportunity it to start a fight.

column1: what i saw in washington yesterday was more ugly and divisive than anything i have seen in american politics so far. it was an insult to victims of sexual violence and a new low for the american political system. i sincerely hope the added negative impact on dr. blasey-ford is something she will be strong enough to recover from.

column2: and don’t support kavanaugh’s confirmation. this current event stirs up many thoughts and feelings for me: i think about the collective sadness survivors feel; i think about the complexities of being a survivor in a country that rewards abusers with the highest powers in office. i feel hopeful that ford’s accusations might receive meaningful attention in pursuit of dismantling rape culture; and i feel hopeless that they might not. i think about who we all might be if we had the same opportunities as white men.

column1: in light of these thoughts and feelings
column2: i’ve found value in reflecting on “naïve cynicism”—a concept introduced to me by one of my favorite authors/mentors/wishful-second-mothers #adoptmeplease
column3: rebecca solnit. regardless of kavanaugh’s probable confirmation
column5: solnit reminds me that “this is how epochal change often begins
column6: with efforts that fail in their direct aims but succeed in shifting the conversation and opening space for further action.” when i notice myself feeling hopeless or cynical
column7: i intend to remember this possibility of space

column1: i intend to recall the collective actions and victories of the #metoo movement (including this very moment) and others like the civil rights movement and #blacklivesmatter #occupywallstreet and #standingrock.  i intend to remember alternatives to cynicism that consider the course of history rather than my often emotionally charged views of the future. i intend to recognize that any one outcome is not the end or the beginning
column2: but is one point on the long road to restoration/rehabilitation. i intend to acknowledge “we often don’t know what is going to happen ahead of time
column3: and an acceptance that whatever takes place will usually be a mixture of blessings and curses that will unfold over considerable time” (solnit). i intend to recognize that cultivating the capacity to respond to oppression with wisdom will require a lot of inner work and community support.

column1: i intend to remember that accumulative actions are what matter most
column2: more than words or attempts to change people’s minds. (continues in comments)";;en;#adoptmeplease

column1: i was molested. i’ve never shared this publicly
column2: but with everything happening in our country lately myself and millions of other survivors are being forced to relive our traumas almost daily. everyone needs to understand the kind of damage sexual assault and abuse have on a person. so i wiil share my story too. .

column1: at age 4 i was repeatedly sexually assaulted by a family member. it continued for years. i carried it with me until i was 12
column2: when i told my parents during an argument. they didn’t believe me
column3: though looking back i see the red flags that i was abused
column4: but nothing ever happened.  i was ashamed
column6: and the abuse had ended; so i buried it. there was nothing i could do if no one believed me. .

column1: throughout the years my trauma would resurface occasionally and i promptly told myself
column4: you’re fine” but lived with the crushing truth that not only was i regularly molested and raped
column5: but he was still out there somewhere
column6: probably doing the same thing to another little girl. .

column1: now at age 33 i am just beginning to see the enormous impact this had on me. my whole life. my sense of self worth
column4: my choices as a parent... i am a different person because of what he did to me. .

column1: i wish i had come forward. if i could go back and do it again i would do it in a heartbeat. if for nothing else than to protect any other children he victimized after me. i’ve been asked why i didn’t report
column2: and there are many reasons i didn’t have the capacity to advocate for myself at the age of 4
column3: but it all really boils down to 2 things: fear and shame. fear of not being believed
column4: fear of hurting someone i loved
column5: fear of being re-traumatized having to relive the experience over and over
column6: and just being ashamed that i wasn’t strong enough to speak up. in fact
column7: every woman i know that was sexually abused or assaulted (which is most of them) says the same thing. so for anyone thinking
column8: “if this is true and all these women were so traumatized why didn’t they come forward at the time?” this is #whyididntreport

column1: 333243;instagram;2018-09-28 17:02:10;FALSE;"i used to think that freedom consists of going on vacations whenever i wanted. it was having a certain dollar amount. not having to work at a desk job.
having all of those things are great but underneath the tangible things
column2: i want the freedom to be me.

column1: this may sound like it's so simple. ""just be yourself."" as if this can happen at a drop of a hat. but it wasn't so simple for me. i couldn't be myself because for my entire life
column4: push aside and be ashamed of certain faces that make up who i am.

column1: it started as childhood conditioning. i wasn't allowed to be angry or upset. crying and screaming to have my emotions acknowledged were met with annoyance
column2: neglect or even punishment. and as an empath child
column3: i could always feel if my requests were happily met or resented. something as basic as asking for a cup of juice for the 3rd time because the person forgot was somehow made to be my fault for being disruptive at 4 years old.

column1: i share this because not much has changed becoming an adult. you're still walking on eggshells with certain people in our lives. you're taking on more than your share of responsibilities because you're not only sick of asking and repeating yourself but you're also sick of being treated like a nag for asking for help. your boundaries aren't being honored because you feel guilty having them in the first place and would rather take on the burden of being physically and emotionally exhausted instead of burdening the other person with the truth of how you feel because you're so depleted that any confrontation makes you sick.
freedom is taking that power back. it means to finally speak your truth and not being afraid to do it. it means to honor your worth
column3: your time and your energy. it means to listen to your intuition the first time around so that you stop putting yourself in compromising situations. it means to be free of anxiety! it means going to bed peacefully and not full of resentment. it meams teaching amd protecting our daughters from being the next #metoo or #whyididntreport

column1: are ypu ready to take your power back and reclaim life?

column1: 333257;instagram;2018-09-28 17:04:36;FALSE;"i stand with one of the many. as a woman who didn’t know until she knew
column2: who didn’t say anything until it felt too late. who avoided confrontation at all cost
column5: and sacrificed my own. as time faded the memories
column6: shame and confusion held strong and would only let me see myself through the broken and shattered dreams that felt stolen from me.

column1: and i stand today with one of the many. who refused to see my future through terminal brokenness. who stood face to face with the pain
column2: went to battle with the humiliation and injustice
column3: rose out of the shadows of fear
column4: and held the grief in my arms until it felt safe to let go.

column1: there is absolutely a battle to be won out on the field
column2: but the ultimate war is the one we have to carry within. the war with depression
column11: and feeling completely and utterly alone.

column2: on the other side of a war that can be won.

column1: once i could believe just because i’ve been damaged
column2: doesn’t mean i am irreparably broken
column3: the chains broke loose. someone may try and take what i have
column4: but they can never take who i am. a woman who uses her broken pieces to become even more whole. a woman who securely knows her value and worth.  a woman who is mastering love in a world that severely lacks it. and a woman called and fully prepared with a mission to help heal and empower all the countless of other beautiful men and women with who i stand with today.

column1: if you are ready to heal from your past and step into your power come find me at www.soulfamilyvip.com. (link in bio) .

column1: 333273;instagram;2018-09-28 17:09:50;FALSE;"thank you @witchthevote (seen via @hauswitch) for this spell… it’s perfect to send gratitude to any and all women (and men) speaking their truth and standing up against sexual predators. ✨🖤✨ we will be appropriating to cast in a future coven class for sure! 🔮🕯✨
a gratitude spell for dr. christine blasey ford
sit or stand wherever you're comfortable. ground yourself and light the candle.
pour some salt into one hand and hold it gently while you write a thank you to dr. ford
column2: something like ""thank you dr. christine blasey ford for your courage and sacrifice"" or even just a simple ""i believe you
column3: i support you"". you can make it a sigil if you want.

column1: now sprinkle your salt over your note
column2: and picture the salt glowing softly

column1: place your hands just above your salted note
column2: not quite touching it. close your eyes and picture all your gratitude and loving support pouring from your hands in the form of warm light. feel its tinglies flowing from your palms and dancing around the note
column3: making the salt sparkle like prisms.

column1: picture the salt absorbing all of the abuse and threats that dr. ford and her family have suffered through this ordeal.
brush the salt off the note
column2: sweeping all that gross energy away with it.

column1: when you feel you've poured all the support you can into the note and cleared all the salt off
column2: picture dr. ford seeing it in front of her
column4: and putting it in her pocket. stay in this space with her for a few moments or longer.

column1: if you'd like to send your note to dr. ford
column2: you can send it to: christine blasey ford c/o rep. anna enshoo 698 emerson st. palo alto
you can roll it up and carry it around like a talisman
column3: bury it in one of your houseplants
column4: or add it to a sacred space.

column1: the end of the spell is to take action. read up on ballot questions
column3: donate to organizations for sexual assault survivors if you can. let survivors know you believe them. don't stop. 🕯🕯🕯 #witchesofaustin #atxwitches #metoo #believesurvivors #gratitude #empwoeredwomenempowerwomen #magicspell";;en;#witchesofaustin

column1: a gratitude spell for dr. christine blasey ford
sit or stand wherever you are comfoable. ground yourself and light the candle.
pour some salt into one hand and hold it gently while you write a thank you to dr. ford
column2: something like ""thank you dr. christine blasey ford for your courage and sacrifice"" or even just a simple ""i believe you
column3: i suppo you"". you can make it a sigil if you want.

column1: now sprinkle your salt over your note
column2: and picture the salt glowing softly

column1: place your hands just above your salted note
column2: not quite touching it. close your eyes and picture all your gratitude and loving suppo pouring from your hands in the form of warm light. feel its tinglies flowing from your palms and dancing around the note
column3: making the salt sparkle like prisms.

column1: picture the salt absorbing all of the abuse and threats that dr. ford and her family have suffered through this ordeal.
brush the salt off the note
column2: sweeping all that gross energy away with it.

column1: when you feel you have poured all the suppo you can into the note and cleared all the salt off
column2: picture dr. ford seeing it in front of her
column4: and putting it in her pocket. stay in this space with her for a few moments or longer.

column1: if you'd like to send your note to dr. ford
column2: you can send it to: christine blasey ford c/o rep. anna enshoo 698 emerson st. palo alto
you can roll it up and carry it around like a talisman
column3: bury it in one of your houseplants
column4: or add it to a sacred space.

column1: 333287;instagram;2018-09-28 17:11:02;FALSE;what is happening in the us currently in relation to the proposed appointment of brett kavanaugh to the supreme court is sobering. it is sobering that in our time of “enlightenment”

column1: 333301;instagram;2018-09-28 17:15:39;FALSE;"if you know me you know i don't love to dwell on the dark days of my past.  but this post and the next - as uncomfortable as they are for me to share
column2: they really are important.  you see what i learned as i worked on trying to ""control"" everything around my injury is that
column3: the desperate need to control was spilling over into every area of my life.  when i shared this talk publicly my original plan was not to share all the dark parts
column4: and as i practiced my talk i realized that without the dark parts it came across as preachy and shallow
column5: and lacked authenticity.  as i dealt with being hurt i also began to face for the first time in my life the shame and unworthiness that came from being raped as a young teen....i had tried to control my experience of this so tightly that i had actually repressed most of my memories of the event.  it's funny how this concussion served as a catalyst for all the memories of that night to come flooding up.  and this time i knew it was time to heal.  so i embarked on a second healing journey
column6: this one focussed on healing the pain that comes from not loving myself.  as i stood on the stage and shared this part of my story i wasn't prepared for the number of women who would come up to me afterwards to thank me for speaking out and then they would share with me their experience of sexual trauma.  what i have learned since then is there is so much power in sharing our stories....not in a way that holds us in the victim role
column7: but sharing our stories in a way that allows us to step into our role of creator of our story.  when we can give voice to the darkness it stops being able to control us
column8: and we can begin to see how some of our biggest strengths were forged in that darkness.  as long as we are sharing that story when we are ready to.  we cannot force anyone to share their traumatic events if they are not ready.  for me - it took me nearly 15 years to be ready.  it was hard and retraumatizing for sure
column9: but i knew i was ready...i couldn't have done it any sooner.⠀

column15: #transformation;;;;;0;;theevolvingalchemist;Kat O'Brien;;0;False;5;0;0;21;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/958ba7a7e9ab995d438118459bb10a59/5D2294D9/t51.2885-15/e35/41836891_468237060349525_7970072320138104768_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"if you know me you know i do not love to dwell on the dark days of my past.  but this post and the next - as uncomfortable as they are for me to share
column16: they really are important.  you see what i learned as i worked on trying to ""control"" everything around my injury is that
column17: the desperate need to control was spilling over into every area of my life.  when i shared this talk publicly my original plan was not to share all the dark parts
column18: and as i practiced my talk i realized that without the dark parts it came across as preachy and shallow
column19: and lacked authenticity.  as i dealt with being hurt i also began to face for the first time in my life the shame and unworthiness that came from being raped as a young teen....i had tried to control my experience of this so tightly that i had actually repressed most of my memories of the event.  it is funny how this concussion served as a catalyst for all the memories of that night to come flooding up.  and this time i knew it was time to heal.  so i embarked on a second healing journey
column20: this one focussed on healing the pain that comes from not loving myself.  as i stood on the stage and shared this part of my story i wasn't prepared for the number of women who would come up to me afterwards to thank me for speaking out and then they would share with me their experience of sexual trauma.  what i have learned since then is there is so much power in sharing our stories....not in a way that holds us in the victim role
column21: but sharing our stories in a way that allows us to step into our role of creator of our story.  when we can give voice to the darkness it stops being able to control us
column22: and we can begin to see how some of our biggest strengths were forged in that darkness.  as long as we are sharing that story when we are ready to.  we cannot force anyone to share their traumatic events if they are not ready.  for me - it took me nearly 15 years to be ready.  it was hard and retraumatizing for sure
column23: but i knew i was ready...i couldn't have done it any sooner.⠀

column1: was transfixed by the senate hearings. i cried while dr. ford conducted herself with composure
column2: honesty and respect. brett kavanaugh yelled
column3: cried and refused to answer questions--he is guilty--there is no doubt in my mind. yet in a few minutes the senate will vote to confirm him. this is not the america i love. i feel my entire being filling up with tears. women’s truths still take a backseat to men’s privilege and expectations.

column1: as all of this is happening i have been reminded that there are still so many among us that believe privilege to be a myth and discrimination a thing of the past. this is where my work starts. why are there still so many people that cannot comprehend the injustice that surrounds us and the changes we are called to make? are they uninformed? misinformed? i think both. while i believe the problem is larger than that
column2: it’s a good place to start. when i founded travels with henry i promised to tell diverse stories. i haven’t been doing a very good job of that lately. this is my promise to you and to myself that i will do better.

column1: 333342;instagram;2018-09-28 17:23:19;TRUE;;"❤️ repost @nicolenelsong: i woke up today missing long talks with my mom (who is also a survivor) we may not be able to talk like that anymore
column2: but her wisdom is still with me

column1: let us all remember who we are. in the face of those in “power” who want us all to be stuck and fighting
column2: who love to see us polarized and constantly distracted - it is important to bring awareness to the fact that breaking us open in this way does not destroy us. we are again
column3: and again reborn. through our very heartache- through witnessing and experiencing the destruction

column1: these issues that are now at the surface of our consciousness - man vs woman
column2: black vs white - these are actually at our roots. it is up to us as individuals to choose
column3: in each moment to define ourselves as much
column4: much more. those of us who are shades of black and brown
column5: those of us who identify as women - we know what it is like to suffer constant indignities at the hands of the ignorant
column6: and narrow minded. we have seen it time and time again
column7: and have learned how to regrow ourselves up from the rubble.

column1: listen to us when we speak because it is coming from a place of direct experience. like it or not
column2: we are a family. we are all at the table together. and yes
column3: the perceived “enemy” does have a seat. but
column4: what is overlooked is this: as deeply as anyone digs in an attempt to uproot us
column5: we further plant into the earth. (she actually helps to pull us in... it is the natural act of the mother. we are not alone in this)

column1: so do not dwell for long in thoughts of hopelessness
column2: and do not let yourself be defined by anyone else’s narrative of who you are or should be. get rooted. breath deeply. connect to your innate wisdom and know your power. you are the embodiment of the whole entire system - the sun and the stars and the earth and everything rolled into one. you will heal
column3: you will be reborn. we all will. #mama #wisdom #healing #love #rebirth #metoo #listen #roots";en;#mama

column1: 333348;instagram;2018-09-28 17:23:48;FALSE;"sexual assault is like a deep wound that is capable only of scabbing over
column2: never fully healing. you are always just a few delicate layers away from opening the wound and experiencing the pain like new.• •

column1: i’ve been on a crusade the last couple weeks. posting tirelessly about @takeourrunsback and sharing my support for survivors of assault. slowly picking at my own scab. each post preparing me to share my story of #whyididntreport -

i was a junior in high school and he was my boyfriend. a person i trusted. i snuck out to go see him that night. i replayed the incident in my head over and over double and triple checking my own memory
column2: i definitely said “no” didn’t i? yes. i made excuses for him
column3: maybe he couldn’t hear me. he could. i berated myself
column4: why didn’t i yell at him after? i just wanted to get out of there. -

column1: i never told my parents. i never told police. at the time i didn’t understand that a boyfriend could rape a girlfriend. all i knew was shame and fear. shame because i blamed myself for having snuck out in the first place. and fear of not being believed
column2: fear of the spectacle it would create. i wrote it many times in my journal only to tear it out for fear of someone reading it. for fear of myself reading it and being reminded. i didn’t know then that i’d never be able to forget it. •

column1: 333366;instagram;2018-09-28 17:28:36;FALSE;"are guys watching? it will be a dark day if kavanaugh is confirmed. a thorough investigation must be done to get the truth. they should not vote yet. even if kavanaugh is not guilty of the sexual assault(i belive he is) the behavior displayed yesterday is ridiculous. it was a job interview. he threatened senators and accused the victims of being part of a conspiracy against him. he does not belong in the supreme court. republicans are so hastily pushing him through the nomination process when there is plenty of time to investigate fully! as senator blumenthal said
column2: why should we confirm him to this lifetime position with a cloud of uncertainty hanging over his head? we will look back on this day with the same disdain we do for the case of anita hill. i know they will not delay the vote though
column3: these white old men simply do not care about sexual assault survivors. by voting yes they are proving their lack of compassion for victims all across america. it sickens me. -em

column6: really. so why am i bringing it up ""so much later?"" because it still matters. because it still effects me. because it impacts every second of my life since it happened. because what ""happened"" isn't even the worst of what ""happens"" to survivors following what ""happened."" because my brain and body's reactions in response to trauma are still happening. it's like ""what happened"" never stops happening. what ""happened to me"" ""so long ago"" is still just as critical and significant in my life today as it was on the actual day(s) it happened. #believewomen #ibelievewomen #metoo #whyididntreport #sexualassaultsurvivor #sexualabusesurvivor";;en;#believewomen

column1: 333425;instagram;2018-09-28 17:37:39;FALSE;"for years now i have considered sharing my personal trauma story with the world at an attempt to heal myself and others. *
this post is not that post. *
this post is simply to show you that we are here. we are all around you. we are your mothers and daughters and your sisters and brothers. we are your student
column3: your best friend and your neighbor. we are scientists and lawyers and doctors and teachers. we are victims and survivors. we love and are loved boldly and unapologetically. we are not burdens. we will not sit back and shut up. we are not less than. we are taking back our lives. we are worth so much more than the things that have been done to us. we are the future. we are the revolution and we will not back down. *

column1: 333426;instagram;2018-09-28 17:37:41;FALSE;"made myself a beautiful lunch on a hard day... i am really thankful to be watching this play out sober. it's fascinating to see the impact of alcohol on our country and how we choose to blame the person rather than the drug

every weekend for the past 19 months i have been so incredibly happy to wake up sober but this weekend when it's so easy to want to escape i will choose sparkling water and baths and long walks with my dog. i choose not to participate in more self harm and instead care for myself with love and compassion 💞

eventhough it's hard we can choose to ignore the messaging that says we need to drink wine or beer to escape this weekend.  instead we can choose our own wellness 🙏

column1: because we’re scared we won’t be believed
we’re scared that we’ll be shamed and bring hurt and shame on our family
because we’re worried it will negatively impact the lives of those we love
we’re worried how it might impact the perpetrator
we’re worried we’ll have to relive it
we’re worried it will put us in more danger
we’re scared of it defining our lives
we’re scared the case will be dropped
we’re scared how it will affect our livelihoods
we’re worried how it will affect their lives
but most of all... we’re scared of breaking.
so thank you professor christine blasey ford for so bravely taking on the system and standing up for women everywhere. we believe you. and we support you.

column1: 333466;instagram;2018-09-28 17:47:00;FALSE;the amount of strength and bravery it takes a person to report sexual assault or abuse is astounding. today had a consultation with a talk thearpist. i gave her a short version of my story and  #whyididntreport because i told myself over and over compared to others experiences it wasn't that bad. how i've tried to repress for years. we came up with a plan on getting through the process. then she said something
column2: something that sent me into a heart racing sobbing panic. she said hopefully we can get to a point where we can confront to the abuser(s). my god i can't even fathom that. i can't even begin to. i'm shaking at the thought. so i want to take a moment to thank those who have the strength to approach their abusers and even harder to take them to court. i have lived with the idea that i take the pain so the other people who love the abuser(s) don't have to hurt... for so long. i don't know if i will ever be able to come forward to that extent. but the respect i have for women and men that come forward is astounding. thank you. i want you survivor's to know even if you don't think it was that bad

column1: 333476;instagram;2018-09-28 17:47:43;FALSE;"i don’t know about you - but this kavanaugh hearing is making my blood boil.
there are so many things i want to say but i have no idea how to and i’m shaking as i type this.
what i know is that i’m angry and devastated for all of the women like dr. ford. i’m angry for the women like me.

some of you know my stories - and most of you don’t. i’m hesitant to share them because i’ve felt firsthand the shame of being blamed for something like ‘provoking the situation’ and i have no desire to repeat that on a public scale. when i was 21
column2: i pressed charges on a man only to be told that my evidence wasn’t good enough to do anything about it.

column1: and that’s what’s wrong with this whole situation. at the end of all of it - we blame victims and use shame and fear as tactics to try and remove their voices. we discredit their voices - even i have spent time wondering if maybe it was all my fault?

so please; let’s listen and respect it when people come forward with their stories. let’s give a voice to those who have been hiding in shame and fear; let’s quit the damn gaslighting and stand in our truths.

i don’t know what my whole point was with this - except that i’ve been there and i’ve been scared too. i’m standing in solidarity with all of these beautiful women + men who are coming forward to make a change in this world. it is far past time. #empoweredliving #metoo #speakup";;en;#empoweredliving

column1: 333488;instagram;2018-09-28 17:50:16;FALSE;"i'm sorry i deleted this i was honestly kind of embarrassed and felt like i shared to much. but i'm going to hold my breathe and share it again. i blamed myself for a while and still do sometimes
column2: that's part if the reason i took it down but over time i've realized that i shouldn't. sharing stories like this make it more and more obvious that this can happen to anybody but it shouldn't.

column1: on december 28th 2017 i went out to a bar in manhattan with some co workers. we were having a nice time but at one point i completely blacked out i'm not sure if it was the drinks or if something had been slipped to me because i've never blacked out for so long. the next thing i kind of remember was waking up naked and alone in a motel room to some man banging on the door telling me i need to get out. i had been brought there
column2: sexually assaulted and left alone. i stumbled out of the hotel i remember crying because i was so foggy i could barely find my way out. i ended up stumbling around the streets of what turned out to be queens until an uber could finally locate me and take me home. my sisters came to ny and took me to the hospital 2 days later. not the day right after because i couldn't even process what happened. i didnt report it and can admit i'm still embarrassed thinking about it because part of me will never know how i was acting. i mean i guess i didnt say ""no"" but how can you when i'm sure i couldn't have even been speaking coherently. anyway i share this with the same intentions as all the other strong women speaking out. i want every women to know
column3: no matter what we stand strong and together. it's never to late to speak up.  i

column1: 333523;instagram;2018-09-28 17:58:05;FALSE;"i believe that the sun will set on this day and better days will be on the horizon.  why i didn’t report:
he was my high school english teacher. he was married with kids and went to my church. i didn’t want to blow up anyone’s life (his or mine). i just wanted him to leave me alone.
i wasn’t a quiet kid in the shadows. i was a straight talking leader. but i was also 16 and didn’t realize if he was hitting on me
column2: he was hitting on other girls too. other girls who wouldn’t tell him to shove it when he showed up late one night to meet our soccer team (he wasn’t a coach and our adult coaches on the bus always made sure we had rides home)
column3: grabbed my hand and asked if he could give me a ride home.  why was this man in a place of power over me trying to get me alone? why was he whispering in my ear that i was “so pretty” during class?

column1: i sat stoney faced and silent in his class for the of the year. i made sure that i was never alone with him.  i told a friend the night it happened as she drove me home from our soccer meet. i told my mom years later and she roared up to the school. but this man had retired early and the school couldn’t share details from his personnel file.

column2: go ahead and confirm who you want. but women who have been sexually abused will never shut up. shut us out and we will just get louder. #metoo #timesup #whyididntreport";;en;#MeToo

column2: i spent yesterday glued to the news. for many of you
column3: the day triggered memories that you long ago put aside
column4: and even struggle to keep out of your daily life. social media was flooded with #metoo stories.

column2: i returned to my 23 year-old self
column3: reliving in vivid detail when i had to take a sick day from my position as a third grade teacher to testify against my abuser. i testified at great personal risk
column4: and i shook in court as i spoke – especially once i realized that i was the one on trial. after 15 minutes of testimony
column5: most of which was from the perpetrator

column2: i often think about the role of our soul's plan
column3: but at the end of the day
column6: feeling it too. if you're feeling triggered by yesterday's hearings
column7: i want to share some wisdom from two master teachers.

column1: from echo bodine: ""the good news about the kavanaugh hearing is that it’s bringing up memories of being sexually abused and with the planets lined up they way they are
column2: all the feelings around being abused are coming up as well.
i’m always looking for the silver lining and it occurred to me this afternoon that this is a healing time for anyone who has been abused in one way or another..."" from robert schwartz
column3: author of your soul's gift and your soul's plan: ""prior to this lifetime
column4: each of us planned to bring to the light of conscious awareness those discordant aspects of self still in need of healing. often
column5: we become aware of these hidden internal aspects through an external trigger...the world reflects us to ourselves so that discordant aspects of consciousness may come into clear view
column6: at which time we may then choose how to relate to them."" almost all humans are a blend of lightness and darkness
column7: and when we are faced with the darkness in our own lives
column8: these elements can be teachers. however
column9: i want to suggest that now is not the time to look for the big lessons. the answers will come in time.

column2: y esta semana fue noticia porque llevó a su primogénita a la cumbre de la onu en eeuu.

column1: ardern se convirtió en primera ministra en octubre. luego de su embarazo
column2: regresó a trabajar el mes pasado después de una licencia por maternidad de seis semanas.

column1: como se encuentra en periodo de lactancia y debía cumplir sus funciones en la asamblea de onu como primera mandataria
column2: no dudó en asistir a la misma con su beba de tres meses!! el embarazo
column3: la maternidad y su gobierno de coalición la han convertido en una figura emblemática del feminismo en el contexto del movimiento #metoo en estados unidos
column4: en donde está teniendo una serie de apariciones en los medios.

column1: porque ser madre y profesional no son roles incompatibles! un aplauso para ella y para su esposo que la acompaño en todo momento. 💪💕💪💕💪💕

column2: and this week it was news because she took her first-born to the un summit in the us.

column1: ardern became prime minister in october. after her pregnancy
column2: she returned to work last month after a six-week maternity leave.

column1: 333560;instagram;2018-09-28 18:05:55;FALSE;"i've never been super public about it
column2: but i am a sexual assault survivor. let me tell you who doubt yourselves: trauma seriously messes up the brain. it confuses it. it is actually a part of the dsm-v diagnostic criteria of ptsd that a person may forget details of the trauma they went through. the brain does whatever it needs to to protect us. for me
column3: this has manifested itself into a permanent state of disassocation
column4: or derealization and depersonalization (if you wanna give it a fancy name). it's been years
column5: and i am still in therapy and actively working on recovery. i believe it's possible

column1: out of sexual assaults reported to police and investigated
column2: only 2% are found to be false accusations. that means it's extremely likely that you know a survivor of sexual assault. many people are
column4: extremely private about their experience. we live in a world of ""what were you wearing"" and ""why were you with them?"" a world that blames the victim over and over
column5: not one that questions the perpetrator. you can make this world better by listening to people's stories and not bombarding them with ""why didn't you do this"" questions. you can make this world better by believing survivors.

column1: i stand with dr. ford. and i hope you do too.

column1: 333561;instagram;2018-09-28 18:06:33;FALSE;"i've never done a #metoo post. i've tried to block out the details. i've tried to hide it away and not think about it. i don’t want to talk about it but with everything happening in the world i feel i have to. i’ve been raped or sexually assaulted by two people and one of those people assaulted me on multiple occassions. i never reported it....because i was drunk
column3: because he was my boyfriend at the time and even though i said ""no""
column4: i said ""i didn't want to"" it was ""ok"" because we were in a committed relationship and had sex before
column5: because the friends i did tell told me it wasn’t rape because i was asking for it.  i will not be silent even though it’s hard to press share today.... i will keep sharing my story in hopes another woman hears it. so she knows she is not alone. so if this happens to her she is able to come forward and speak to someone about it. so she doesn't have to spend 15 years of her life trying to pretend everything is ok and trying to repress the awful memories. #ibelieveher #ibelieveyoutoo #believesurvivors #itsnotyourfault #metoomovement";;en;#metoo

column1: 333570;instagram;2018-09-28 18:11:37;FALSE;"do you have free will? probably not as much as you thought... do you feel like you have free will?
or... do you feel like you're just floating along through life completely out of control? ... like others are dictating where your life will go?
i've felt like this for many many years.
how do we stop this from happening?

column2: it all starts with taking responsibility for everything.

column1: when i say this a lot of people get upset because they think i'm telling them to blame themselves.
when you take responsibility for everything you feel a sense of power. not a sense of weakness.
it's when you look at your life and realize you have control.
you may not have control over certain situations
column2: but you have control over how you react

column1: most people build invisible fences around themselves that block them off from their true potential.
here is one of my favorite steve jobs quotes... ""when you grow up you tend to get told the world is the way it is and you're life is just to live your life inside the world.
try not to bash into the walls too much. try to have a nice family
life can be much broader once you discover one simple fact: everything around you that you call life was made up by people that were no smarter than you and you can change it
column3: you can build your own things that other people can use.

column2: you'll never be the same again."" read that again and really let it sink in... think about all the walls you've put up around your life.

column1: what are some things that are holding you back?

column3: or thoughts that prevent you from trying something new?

column1: many of us are lucky enough to live in a free country... but... how many of us are truly free?
think about it... if you want to learn how to identify and change these limiting beliefs check out my free training below

column1: 333624;instagram;2018-09-28 18:21:19;FALSE;"i’m sure you have all heard about dr christine blasey ford’s statement
column2: it’s taken over social media and the news. i was reading over a post earlier and reading the comments left me feeling sick to my stomach.

column1: when did we loose our humanity?
the comments i read on a post earlier were saying;
“we don’t believe you christine you are a pawn and a greedy one and soon you will go back to being a nobody.”
to everybody who is leaving comments all over social media i hope you know how much you are damaging people
column2: not dr. christine as such but other women and men who have yet to tell their story.

column1: i hope you understand the damage this message will be doing to victims all over the world who have yet to tell their story
column2: who are living in fear not getting the help and justice they need.

column1: not because i have listened to all the evidence or the trial.
but because every single victim deserves the respect and the support they need.
every single victim deserves to be heard.
every single victim has battled a demon to tell their story.
so christine blasey ford i believe you.

column1: 333638;instagram;2018-09-28 18:25:30;FALSE;"🇪🇸 los narcisistas mantienen a sus ex-parejas cerca para una obtener mayor atención y triangulación. usan a sus exes para sentirse deseados en todo momento
column2: y para crear competencia y celos con sus parejas actuales. sus ex se pueden clasificar en 2 categorías: 1. enamorados de él 2. locos. los ""locos"" son los que vieron las mentiras narcisistas y se negaron a participar en sus juegos. los ""enamorados"" todavía creen que desempeñan algún tipo de papel especial en su vida. cuando el narcisista se queda sin víctimas
column3: recicla los viejos objetivos. pero las únicas personas verdaderamente felices son los supuestos locos que le dieron la espalda y dejaron atrás todo el drama fabricado. ❤✒: uk. 🇺🇸 narcissist keep their exes strung along for added attention and triangulation. they use their exes to appear in high demand at all times
column4: creating competition and jealousy with their current partners. their exes can usually be placed into 2 categories: 1. in love with him 2. crazy. ""the crazy"" exes are the ones who saw through the narcissist lies and refused to take part in their games anymore. column1: 333644;instagram;2018-09-28 18:26:00;FALSE;"hero. this photo gives me shivers. haven’t we all felt this sort of fear
as we are put on trial
as we share our experiences of trauma
as we know we won’t be believed
as we know we will be rejected
as we faithfully do what is right anyway
as we hope for something better
as we illuminate what life could be where we all thrive and where all are truly welcomed and safe
as we take down systems and institutions with better stories...
we are here and we won’t leave.
i remember that jesus commanded the dead girl to rise
commended the woman who poured perfume on his head out of love
trusted the woman at the well to be an an evangelist in her neighborhood
believed the woman caught in adultery and saved her life
welcomed his friend mary as a disciple at his feet

column3: to first preach the good news of his resurrection and to his male disciples no less.

column1: i haven’t had a panic attack in years.

column2: angry old men disgraced her and flippantly shrugged her off like the nuisance they think she is

column2: i’ve acquired the tools to quickly get my panic attack under control. so
column3: i am turning my panic into focus-driven energy and action
column4: so that my actions may help to bring about change
column6: and for everyone. i will write. i will make phone calls. i will vote. i will vote. i will vote.

column1: 333707;instagram;2018-09-28 18:38:25;FALSE;"i came home from zumba earlier and recorded a raw and vulnerable episode of my podcast soulful conversations with nadjejda where i shared a part of my story that only a few people know about me. i never thought about sharing it on that platform or any other public platform for a long time but i was inspired and moved to do so after dr. ford’s testimony yesterday and some of the reactions to it.

i was concerned i’d changed my mind if i waited until after i shower so i recorded the video still sweaty from class. sharing this here as a way to hold myself accountable and share it publicly for sure next week. #metoo #believesurvivors #believewomen #mystory #mytruth #selflove #selfloveeducator #coach #spiritualteacher #blackgirlmagic #author #transformationandleadershipstrategist #womenwholead #useyourvoice #speakup";;en;#metoo

column1: 333718;instagram;2018-09-28 18:39:39;FALSE;"i haven’t made a permanent post in a couple months because i wanted my #500thpost to be important. i finally feel like i have a reason.
believe women. stop questioning those that come out as victims of a crime- no one questions the victims of violent robberies or car jacking. -

women are not different or special because they are related to you or you have feelings for them- all women are people and deserve to be treated with humanity regardless of who they are to you. if you need to label them as something else just to sympathize
column2: you are part of the problem.

column1: i believe dr. ford and i still believe anita hill’s testimony. women don’t report sexual assault years later for fame or notoriety
column2: but out of a rotting feeling of absolute torment that has plagued them for years- a torment worsened by realizing that the person who unspeakably wronged you is being rewarded without ever having to answer for their crime. no one asks for anita hill’s autograph all these years later because her story was not told so that she could ride anyone’s coat tails to a better social status. most of you didn’t know who anita was until dr. ford was in the news. speaking out against “powerful men” doesn’t make us vindictive or wrong
column3: there is no agenda other than to demand that justice is served.

column1: most of us refuse to report sexual assault because we are afraid that everyone will believe the perpetrator more than us. in all these years gone by
column2: i have never reported my assault to any law authority because who would people believe? who would people actually question- me? even now those of you reading this are questioning me. you come from a place of judgment and bias
column3: whether you realize it or not
column4: and that is why i have never demanded justice for myself- justice is rarely seen for most of us. -

column2: for the men who are taking all of this rhetoric about assault and victim’s rights personally
column3: maybe you should try smiling. it will make you look prettier
column4: or at least that’s what i’ve been told by guys like you my whole damn life.

column1: i am not sorry about your fragile masculinity.

column1: why? because after my first experience of sexual harassment at work
column2: i reported it to my boss along with a female co-worker who was cornered in a room by another male associate and solicited for sex during her solo morning shift. our boss only believed us because the male employee had a history of doing this
column3: but that wasn’t enough to fire him. he expected us to continue working with this guy
column4: but without any expectation for our assaulter to take responsibility for his continued harassment of female employees. i had the security to walk away from the job
column5: he had the privilege to keep it & my coworker had no choice but to stay because she had medical bills to pay. .

column2: no matter the evidence? this is an epidemic.

wanting to crawl under a rock and cry

column1: and i’m guessing yours is too. heavy for all the female identified people who are feeling triggered by yesterday’s proceedings. for all the women who’ve stayed silent. who’ve felt less than. not worthy. afraid.
it’s often to hard to know what to do in moments like these — but if there’s one thing i do know is that it looks different for each of us — for some
column2: it’s to fight back and be a voice. for others
column3: it’s to retreat and self preserve.

column2: and i knew that. (but i also knew i had a lot of shit to take care of) but as someone who preaches self care to her clients on the daily
column3: i knew that i needed to practice what i preach.

column1: so i did just that and dropped everything for a few hours and drove to my favorite place 40 mins outside of the city to spend the morning unplugged and in nature with toby.
and i ran with my dog through grassy fields.
and soaked in the crisp fall air.
and i put away my phone.
don’t be afraid to do what you need to do for your heart
column2: my love. that is a powerful thing and god knows we need more women rising into their truth now more than ever.

column7: that i did nothing to stop.  the questions i didn’t ask.  the comfo i did not offer.  the accommodations i made to perpetrators of violence.  the denials of the survivors’ experiences.  the rejections of their truth.

column3: and college are hard.  to those i grew up with
column4: we grew up in a culture of rape.  i cannot say nothing anymore. to the survivors
column5: i am sorry.  i believe you.

column1: 333837;instagram;2018-09-28 19:06:44;FALSE;"i’m not one for these kinds of posts. but i feel i must say something about the events this week. .
we cannot victim shame this woman. whether what she claims happened or not
column2: that is not for us to tell her. our job is to lend an empathetic ear and hear her out. to reach out a hand and support her. sexual assault is real. not speaking out is real. feeling like it could have been worse and it wasn’t so you lock it inside is real. girl and boys and men and women who are watching this with a wound in their hearts and their minds are seeing the color of the people around them. they are seeing that they can’t speak up. that they will be judged and ridiculed and threatened and harassed. that what happened to them doesn’t matter because the perpetrator will always win the day. and we cannot allow that to happen. your voice is always important
column3: and you should always be believed.

column2: and my heart is always open to you
column3: whoever you are. i believe her. and i believe you. .

column1: i am here with my tears to join in with yours. i am here with my #metoo story. i feel you. i feel your hopelessness. your rage. i feel your pain.
but i am also here to tell you that we are not just survivors! we are overcomers! even on days like today where it's too much to get out of bed. when we just can't hear.one.more.word. from the media.
the patriarchy is going down. we are the granddaughter's of the witches they couldn't burn.

i am a daughter of lilith. so are you. she walks with us during these dark times. rage. write. do whatever you have to do to get through. they cannot silence us. they cannot stop the force we are. we are creator!

5 key things to know about the current situation facing the genders:⠀

column2: primarily through men has become an obvious crisis in our society and culture. ⠀

column1: ✨the shadow masculine is a rogue energy and is harmful and painful.  it’s insidious and systemic in nature. it’s a mindset of separation that destroys. ⠀
✨the shadow masculine offers all of us an opportunity to be better human beings.⠀
✨this crisis offers us a great opportunity to evolve beyond the problems that we face both individually and collectively. ⠀
✨men are at an early stage in their process to own their shadow and take the journey to rediscover the wonderful things about being a man. ⠀
9 vitally important things men can do right now:⠀
✨to take radical responsibility with my words and actions⠀
✨to be radically respectful of women and all things feminine.⠀
✨to understand that they are not alone #wetoo⠀
together we can navigate the challenges we face. we men

column3: have your back and who are ready to follow your lead. as a man i suggest that #women lead with the #wisdom
column4: #grace and #love of your true feminine #nature. that way we men can get onboarded quickly and not project out the shadow masculine in an even more destructive manner. ⠀

column2: we must do better. it’s no longer acceptable to quietly sit back as our portion of society deems it okay to dismiss the very real problems surrounding sexual assault and rape. it’s time to speak out against those who downplay any and all accusations brought forth by victims of these crimes. it’s time for men to hold other men accountable first and foremost. stop victim blaming. stop victim shaming. stop slandering the names of women who are finally finding the courage to speak out against those in power. sexual assault has many faces
column3: and none of them are any more acceptable than the other. if you question the validity of an accusation before you question the character of the person being accused
column4: i ask that you start thinking more critically about your moral standards. women need our support. they don’t need solemn and quiet men anymore. they need men who are willing to believe

column4: the uproarious laughter and their having fun at my expense” i started shaking. i remember the laughter too.

column2: i was driven to a self storage unit and was sexually assaulted in the back of a coupe car by two guys i thought we’re friends. one of them had just joined the secret service. he made a mistake. he didn’t know he assaulted the family member of a respected secret service agent. i reported to my family immediately. and he was removed from the agency. i never reported to the authorities. why? his father was the sheriff. and my teenage self thought i wouldn’t be believed
column3: i would be made fun of even more at school and him being denied authority was justice enough for me. i didn’t report because i was scared. he always had a gun on his waist. his face and hands coming towards me still appears in my dreams to this day. putting the pain and fear deep away was what
column5: the best option. not knowing it would effect the way i go about living my adult life.

column1: 333906;instagram;2018-09-28 19:19:08;FALSE;"i am sure i am not alone when i say that the u.s senate hearing has stirred up many different emotions. i tossed and turned last night unable to get a good night sleep and it has been difficult to articulate my emotions
column2: laying in bed last night these words kept running through my head so i thought i would share:

column1: i love you with all of my heart
column2: but as connected as we are you will never know in totality the path i must walk.

column1: you will never know the mapping of my development where i learned that sensitivity and emotions were weak. boys don't cry..sound familiar?
you will never know the body dysphoria shaped from being ""too flat"" ""too curvy"" ""too tall"" ""too skinny"" ""too muscular""
you will never know the confusion felt that night that he kissed a little too hard
column2: held down a little too aggressive

column1: you will never know the shame felt when you didn't speak out
column2: for fear you would be to blame.

column1: you will never know the annoyance when it is assumed that you are the secretary
you will never know how it feels to walk down the street alone after dark
column3: holding your keys between your fingers and scanning every escape route possible.

column1: you will never know this path we walk
column2: because you were not born a woman. xoxo cass

column1: 333946;instagram;2018-09-28 19:27:10;FALSE;it is with so much pain and heart wrenching reluctance i post this. i sit here shaking with tears streaming down my cheek as i continue reciting my recent mantra and pledge. i will expand my life and do all i can to help my fellow survivors. how can i expect others to be brave and speak out when i stay silent and continue to live with this internal fear? even despite all my efforts to move through it and carry it with me as a torch instead of a burden. something i believe i am beginning to succeed at. if one in three women have experienced sexual abuse or assault then it is most likely i will reach someone who is still living in silence from a similar experience or trauma. this is why i am stopping my own silence. for a few years i was terrified to do this for the wrong reasons or have ulterior motives that i didn’t even realize
column2: but now i can stand in confidence and say i am doing this because even if i reach only one person
column3: this utterly exhausting and depleting banter will be worthwhile. the importance of speaking up isn’t a call for attention or pity
column4: it’s to tell those others that still live in shame and fear that it will be okay. we do not want to be looked at differently or with fragile eyes. we want empathy and support and respect. what dr. ford has shown this week has inspired so many of us and will for years to come. i am not yet as brave as her to tell my story to everyone but i have no doubt i will be and i will stand up and speak with a louder voice for all women and men who know this hell of a reality. for now
column5: all i have the courage to say is #metoo. we are being told by the highest court in the ‘most free’ country that our bodies are less than. that our pain and lifelong trauma caused by these experiences is not important. that we are unworthy because pushing politics is more important than our bodies
column7: and hearts. i have never been more distraught by a pending political decision in my lifetime and the past two days i have especially been outraged and devastated and invalidated. i’ve been fortunate enough to have been able to stand in rooms this week where women from all over can gather in our pain and remind ourselves we are not alone. the;;en;#metoo.;;;;;0;;livingloopholes;↣ ? column1: 333956;instagram;2018-09-28 19:28:45;FALSE;"i don’t get very involved with politics on social media.  i try to stay informed
column3: i stand back.  one of my areas of work and inquiry at this point in my life is to consciously step out of the fray.  my mo is quite the opposite
column4: as a result of many things that have happened in my life—i want to fight. i want to stand up for every last underdog.  i want to put my finger in the face of the bully and reveal them for what they are. but it's not always good for me to get so worked up--physically and mentally.

column2: there are occasions where i simply must speak up—this is one of them.

column1: what have i heard that upsets me?  my goodness….. *if it really happened
column2: why would she wait so long to report this? *if she knew of other women who had been assaulted etc
column3: why did she not report it? *people don’t change that drastically. to go from a sexual predator at 15 to a stellar citizen as an adult.

column1: i have spent a lot of time in the last 48 hours just staring blankly out into nothing—perplexed.  i don’t understand how anyone
column2: with their finger even remotely on the pulse of the #metoo movement could pose any of the above questions.

column4: have more than one story to share as it pertains to being sexually assaulted.  i feel like that’s important to mention. i’m going to share some things

column1: when i was in high school
column2: i was sexually assaulted by someone i was dating. i said “no” several times—he didn’t care.

column1: i have spent so many hours thinking about this moment in my life. this relationship and what i chose to do in the days
column2: weeks and years following this incident. what is clear is that for a long time
column3: i didn’t think what had happened was assault because he was my “boyfriend”. there are people who raise the question “why did she wait so long” as a way to discredit dr. ford.  there are so many reasons i didn’t report the person who assaulted me—the misguided belief that what he did was allowed because we we’re dating at the time. fear.  shame.  it doesn’t matter that it took me years to actually speak about it and be able to say with assertion that i was harmed in that way. it still happened.

column2: the current state of the news and social media is hard. being told your abuser is innocent is hard. having people excuse their behavior because they were drunk but being told it wouldn’t have happened if you had had a few less drinks is hard. feeling like your body belongs to anyone but you is hard. not being listened to or even heard is hard. the lack of empathy people have is hard. this country no longer feels like home. my own body no longer feels like home. coming out about sexual abuse will not ruin someone’s life

column2: i haven't really engaged in the #metoo social media space. when i started my gender studies degree in 2008
column3: none of this was mainstream. i was called a feminist as an insult. i didn’t yet have a huge group of friends who identified as such. i was shoved
column5: and called names while doing (peaceful) activism work. there was little support. self care wasn’t really a thing. there were few safe spaces. it was nearly impossible to talk about these issues anywhere except in specialized groups or in private. when i did speak out publicly about difficult subjects
column6: i was met with silence (apathy) or dissonance. it was fucking exhausting. i got tired. i got quieter… well

column3: things have slowly started to change. leaving out the factions of pop culture that have co-opted feminist rhetoric for shallow commercial purposes
column4: i am so so happy that words like “equality” and “feminism” are now usually met with agreement rather than a rolling of the eyes. but we have so far to go
column5: and some days reading the news makes it feel like we are moving backwards. i still don’t always have the energy or words to engage publicly
column6: even though i am privately exceptionally preoccupied with the current political landscape and remain firmly invested in issues such as women’s health

column1: this kavanaugh bullshit has compelled me to break my online quietness to say this:

column2: you can keep getting enraged at finally (finally) being held accountable for your actions. we’ve been enraged for a long time. and now
column3: that anger is turning into action. i believe survivors. we believe survivors. enjoy the last days of rome
column4: cis white men. because your time up there alone on the throne is ending. move over & welcome to the real world; there are consequences here.
